ntiated curriculum within their grades. We had my oldest IQ tested and the psychologist urged us to get her into a challenging curriculum...or deal with disengagement. A ability instead of age based class would eliminate the urge to redshirt kids and also end &quot;early promotion&quot; of kids. While it would take more work on a school admin's part to figure out where a child should be (as opposed to just dividing up a group of similarly aged kids into same sized groups) it would be better for children across the board. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="824" language="en" documentId="5273" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Mama Marconi" date="November 13, 2012 at 10:15 am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://schoolsofthought.blogs.cnn.com/2012/11/12/my-view-kindergarten-redshirting-different-for-each-child/comment-page-1" topic="redshirting" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="5273" notes="" title="My View: Kindergarten redshirting different for each child"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="824"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>